Maximum Fund Return on Target Allocation
Medium Dynamic Programming Finance / Banking
Problem Statement
A bank has N investment funds available for clients. Each fund is described by two attributes:
Allocation amount (in units, e.g. ₹ thousands) — how much capital this fund requires.
Annual return rate (in %) — the percentage return this fund generates.
A client wants to invest exactly T units of capital. You must select a subset of funds such that their allocation amounts sum to exactly T. Among all valid subsets, return the maximum total profit the client can earn.

The profit from each selected fund is calculated as:
profit_i = (allocation_i × return_rate_i) / 100
The total profit is the sum of profits of all selected funds. If no valid subset sums to exactly T, return -1.
Input Format
Line 1: N T           (number of funds, target allocation)
Next N lines: A[i] R[i]  (allocation amount, return rate)
Output Format
A single number: maximum profit (rounded to 2 decimal places)
Print -1 if no valid subset exists.
Constraints
1 ≤ N ≤ 100
1 ≤ T ≤ 10,000
1 ≤ A[i] ≤ 1,000 (allocation, multiple of 10)
1 ≤ R[i] ≤ 50 (return rate %)
All allocations are positive integers.
